      Is Elon Musk going to take over Twitter?
   =20
 =20
No? I mean, what do I know. But it seems unlikely. Here are Bloomberg=E2=80=
=99s  Liana Baker and Scott Deveau:Elon Musk=E2=80=99s decision to reject a=
 board seat at Twitter Inc. leaves the company=E2=80=99s management, invest=
ors and interested observers with one big question: What will the richest m=
an in the world do next?With a fortune of $250 billion, it might seem like =
there=E2=80=99s not much standing between Musk and a full takeover of the s=
ocial media network (if that=E2=80=99s what he wants, and he=E2=80=99s hint=
ed before that he might indeed be after his own platform). But public compa=
nies like Twitter are bound by a lot of small print, including corporate by=
laws that could stop Musk from building up his position and make a hostile =
bid pretty difficult.I assume that Elon Musk bought 9.1% of Twitter Inc.=E2=
=80=99s stock because it seemed fun and didn=E2=80=99t cost=C2=A0that=C2=A0=
much. He spent about $2.6 billion on the stock, which was money that he had=
 lying around because last year he=C2=A0 sold about $16 billion of Tesla In=
c. stock=C2=A0as part of a complicated scheme to troll people on Twitter. P=
resumably much of the $16 billion went to pay taxes on the sales, and on hi=
s=C2=A0stock option exercises, but  not all of it, and he probably didn=E2=
=80=99t spend much of=C2=A0the rest. Musk=E2=80=99s lifestyle is not all th=
at expensive. He sleeps at the office (or his friend=E2=80=99s mansion) and=
=C2=A0disdains possessions; his only real indulgence is=C2=A0online trollin=
g. That is an expensive hobby, though, at least the way he does it. His  pr=
etend takeover of Tesla cost him a few million dollars,[1] his Tesla=C2=A0s=
ales cost a few billion in unnecessary taxes, the Twitter purchases cost a =
few billion more, but look at the pleasure he got out of each of them.On th=
e other hand if he tried to buy the=C2=A0rest=C2=A0of Twitter he=E2=80=99d =
be looking at spending another $40 billion or so.[2] That is a fraction of =
his net worth, but it is probably a lot more cash than he has lying around,=
 and I=E2=80=99m not sure he would want to sell $55=C2=A0billion of Tesla s=
tock=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0about a third of his stake, and the most liquid pa=
rt of his wealth=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0to buy Twitter.[3]Traditionally if you=
 are going to do a takeover of a public company you raise some outside fina=
ncing. If he wanted to buy Twitter I suppose Musk could get some=C2=A0equit=
y financing from the Saudi sovereign wealth fund, hahahaha no I=E2=80=99m s=
orry let=E2=80=99s not even joke about that, Elon Musk is not doing another=
 takeover with  pretend equity financing from the Saudis. In general I do n=
ot know why anyone would want to be an equity partner with Elon Musk on buy=
ing Twitter. He=E2=80=99s going to be making all of the decisions, and he=
=E2=80=99s not going to be making those decisions to maximize cash flow.=C2=
=A0I suppose he could raise debt financing from banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0Twitte=
r currently has a couple billion dollars of bonds outstanding with BB ratin=
gs and 5%-ish yields =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is hard to imagine raising much.=
 Bloomberg tells me that Twitter trades at an enterprise value of around 60=
 times estimated 2022 earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amo=
rtization; banks aren=E2=80=99t supposed to lend more than about six times =
EBITDA. Twitter=E2=80=99s cash flow from operations last=C2=A0year was abou=
t $632 million, which is just not going to support anywhere close to the de=
bt required for a takeover. That=E2=80=99s leaving aside the fact that an E=
lon Musk-owned Twitter would be far more chaotic than a regular public Twit=
ter.Maybe he could get a margin loan from a bank against his Tesla stock an=
d use the money=C2=A0to buy Twitter? That would be pretty wild. I would not=
 bet on it. (Musk has already pledged about half his Tesla shares to secure=
 personal loans, and Tesla in theory has rules limiting his ability to borr=
ow more.)Other than the money, though, there is not much about Twitter that=
 would prevent a takeover. It does not have dual-class stock that would kee=
p its founders in control, and the founders are no longer in charge and don=
=E2=80=99t even own that much stock. It is not in a heavily regulated indus=
try,=C2=A0and there=E2=80=99s no particular antitrust problem with=C2=A0Mus=
k acquiring it. =E2=80=9CWorld=E2=80=99s richest person acquires the main v=
enue for public communication=E2=80=9D does=C2=A0seem=C2=A0like the sort of=
 thing that ought to=C2=A0raise regulatory concerns, but in our actually ex=
isting system I=E2=80=99m not sure what those concerns=C2=A0would be.=C2=A0=
Like pretty much every U.S.=C2=A0public company, Twitter has the ability to=
 put in place a poison pill to fend off a hostile takeover, but that doesn=
=E2=80=99t mean much. If Elon Musk offers to pay a cash premium for all of =
Twitter=E2=80=99s stock, the board will only stop him if it can credibly sa=
y =E2=80=9Cno, this offer is bad for shareholders, our plan for the standal=
one business=C2=A0offers much more long-term value than Musk=E2=80=99s cash=
.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s a thing that happens often enough in hostile take=
overs, but here it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Twitter =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0Elon Musk. If you are a Twitter director confronted with an Elon Musk=
 hostile takeover proposal, and you put in a poison pill to block him, then=
:=09You=E2=80=99ll definitely get sued.=09He=E2=80=99ll run a proxy fight t=
o try to vote you out, and an army of retail investors will buy the stock a=
nd vote with him.[4]=09He will tweet so many mean things about you, and tho=
se mean tweets will get lots of engagement.=09Your defense will be like =E2=
=80=9Cno, we know what we are doing, we are excellent at maximizing long-te=
rm value for our shareholders and we have a viable plan to make Twitter vas=
tly more valuable in the future,=E2=80=9D which is somewhat empirically dou=
btful.=09If you prevail and Musk=E2=80=99s offer goes away, he=E2=80=99ll p=
robably quit Twitter in a huff, you=E2=80=99ll lose your noisiest user, the=
 stock will drop and you=E2=80=99ll get sued some more.=09It=E2=80=99s just=
 very very unpleasant you know?If Musk launched a credible cash takeover bi=
d the board would really have no choice but to negotiate with him. (If the =
bid said =E2=80=9CI have $40 billion of financing secured for this bid, but=
 I can=E2=80=99t tell you anything else about it,=E2=80=9D the negotiations=
 would be very annoying.) I just don=E2=80=99t think he=E2=80=99ll do it.Wh=
y would he? For one thing, his interest in Twitter is mostly about amusing =
himself. And he has plenty of control now.=C2=A0As its biggest shareholder,=
 noisiest user and the richest person in the world, he can easily get a mee=
ting with Twitter management any time he wants, and tell them to do whateve=
r he wants, and they have to listen respectfully and consider doing it. If =
they say =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D too often, he can threaten things like =E2=80=
=9CI will tweet mean things about you, on Twitter,=E2=80=9D which will be g=
enuinely unpleasant for them:=E2=80=9CTwitter has always suffered more than=
 its fair share of dysfunction,=E2=80=9D said Jason Goldman, who was on Twi=
tter=E2=80=99s founding team and served on its board of directors in the pa=
st. =E2=80=9CBut at least we weren=E2=80=99t being actively trolled by pros=
pective board members using the product we created.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CWe cre=
ated the most powerful tool for trolling that the world has ever seen, and =
we cheered=C2=A0when Elon Musk used it to troll people, but we were not exp=
ecting him to use it to troll us,=E2=80=9D okay thanks.If tweeting mean thi=
ngs doesn=E2=80=99t work, Musk could threaten a proxy fight, in which he co=
uld use his large block of shares and influence with retail investors to vo=
te out some directors and vote in some of his own directors to do his biddi=
ng. This threat seems implausible given that (1) Twitter has a staggered bo=
ard, so he cannot obtain a majority in one proxy fight, (2) a proxy fight i=
s a lot like having lawyers write mean tweets for you, and Musk prefers to =
write the=C2=A0tweets himself,=C2=A0and (3)=C2=A0  he just turned down a bo=
ard seat. The point of a proxy fight is to get on the board of a company th=
at doesn=E2=80=99t want you on its board; Twitter wants Musk on its board a=
nd he said no.Or he can threaten to=C2=A0do a hostile takeover of Twitter,=
=C2=A0and then Twitter=E2=80=99s managers can go read this column and feel,=
 like, a=C2=A0little=C2=A0reassured, but not=C2=A0totally=C2=A0reassured. T=
he fact that it makes no sense for Elon Musk to do a hostile takeover of Tw=
itter is not absolute proof that he won=E2=80=99t do a hostile takeover of =
Twitter! The threat remains alarming; they have to take it seriously.Musk c=
ould also just buy more stock in the open market, but what does that accomp=
lish? It gives him more of a toehold for a proxy fight or a hostile takeove=
r, but if he=E2=80=99s not going to do those things then owning more stock =
doesn=E2=80=99t matter. Also, he=E2=80=99s at 9.1% now, and if he goes over=
 10% he would be subject to stricter limits under U.S. securities laws. In=
=C2=A0particular, his ability to=C2=A0actively trade the stock, buying and =
selling whenever the mood strikes him, would be limited. So why bother?Most=
ly my guess is that Musk enjoys being able to tell Twitter what to do and d=
oes not care very much about it actually getting done. I could be wrong her=
e, but tweeting about accepting Dogecoin for Twitter=E2=80=99s paid subscri=
ption tier  seems like more fun than supervising its implementation. If he =
buys Twitter he has to make decisions; Twitter is his problem. If he owns 9=
% of Twitter he can just troll; he is=C2=A0Twitter=E2=80=99s problem.[5]=C2=
=A0Oh incidentally Twitter filed the proxy statement for its annual meeting=
 today and it reports that Musk owns 68.9 million shares? Which is less tha=
n the 73.1 million shares that Musk has reported? Twitter=E2=80=99s footnot=
e:Consists of 68,943,938 shares held of record as of the Record Date by the=
 Elon Musk Revocable Trust dated July 22, 2003, for which Mr. Musk serves a=
s the sole trustee. Mr. Musk reported holdings of 73,115,038 shares held as=
 of April 4, 2022 pursuant to a Schedule 13D filed with the SEC on April 5,=
 2022.I don=E2=80=99t know! Musk got the number wrong=C2=A0in one of his ow=
n filings, so I can=E2=80=99t be sure that his number is right now, though =
I think his number is more likely to be right than Twitter=E2=80=99s is.[6]
