   =20
      Newswire insider trading
   =20
 =20
The main way to insider trade is to know big news about public companies be=
fore the news is public. If you work at a public company, you will occasion=
ally learn big news about your company before it is public, and then you ca=
n trade on it, but (1) there will not be that many opportunities and (2) yo=
u will probably get caught and get in trouble. If you want to insider trade=
 a lot, the better place to be is at some intermediary that regularly gets =
big news about=C2=A0many=C2=A0public companies just before it becomes publi=
c. So investment bankers and mergers-and-acquisitions lawyers are classic i=
nsider traders: They learn big news (mergers) about many different companie=
s (their clients) before the news is public. Still you will only have so ma=
ny clients, and also you=E2=80=99ll get caught.For really ambitious insider=
 trading, the ideal intermediary is one of the companies that takes big new=
s from lots of companies, holds on to it briefly, and then makes it public.=
 We  talked a few months ago about Edgarizers, the=C2=A0companies that =E2=
=80=9Cprovide proprietary, cloud-based software platforms to facilitate pub=
lic companies=E2=80=99 filing of periodic and other reports with the SEC.=
=E2=80=9D A company has some news, it puts the news in a Securities and Exc=
hange Commission filing, it sends the filing to a service provider to file =
with the SEC. Sometimes it sends the filing to the service provider=C2=A0ea=
rly:=C2=A0It maintains a draft on the provider=E2=80=99s system, it finaliz=
es the draft on that system over hours or days, and=C2=A0then=C2=A0it hits =
the filing button. If you hack into the service provider, as a Russian mili=
tary intelligence officer allegedly did, then you can get lots of SEC filin=
gs early and trade on them and make money.But the real prizes are the newsw=
ires, the companies that transmit press releases for companies. Any time a =
company has big news it is going to put out a press release, and sometimes =
companies will upload their press releases to the newswires hours or days b=
efore they are final. If you hack into the newswires, as some Ukrainian hac=
kers=C2=A0did  a few years ago, you can get lots of press releases early an=
d trade on them and make money.If you=C2=A0work=C2=A0at a newswire then I g=
uess you can also do that, but you are more likely to get caught? Here is a=
 fun story out of Canada:Two Toronto-area programmers for GlobeNewswire, on=
e of the largest wire services in the world, are under investigation as par=
t of an insider-trading probe launched by the Ontario Securities Commission=
, The Globe and Mail has learned.The regulator alleges that two software de=
velopers for Intrado Corporation, the U.S.-based telecommunications company=
 that owns GlobeNewswire, regularly texted each other about draft corporate=
 press releases scheduled to be issued, and executed trades on that materia=
l, non-public information. ...The court records show that GlobeNewswire mai=
ntains an electronic system for tracking employees who click on news releas=
es before they are publicly issued =E2=80=93 which might have offered a pot=
ential clue about employees who traded based on that information.However, [=
OSC investigator Anthony] Long said that investigators had learned of a wor=
karound, where employees could hover their cursor over a partial headline, =
which would reveal the entire headline =E2=80=9Cwithout leaving an audit tr=
ail.=E2=80=9DWe have  talked about the fact that the newswire hackers, who =
had the full text of lots of not-yet-public press releases, had about a 77%=
 success rate: About three-quarters of the time, they would read a press re=
lease and buy (or sell) the stock and the stock would go up (or down), as t=
hey predicted. The other quarter of the time they would read the press rele=
ase and think =E2=80=9Caha good news=E2=80=9D and buy the stock and then th=
e press release would come out and the stock would go down. It is not easy =
to read a press release and know if it is good or bad news. The market migh=
t have already expected the good news in the headline, and it might instead=
 focus obsessively on the one little bit of bad news in paragraph 11.=C2=A0=
It seems like a fun exercise to insider trade by=C2=A0only=C2=A0mousing ove=
r the headlines of unreleased press releases.=C2=A0Every=C2=A0earnings rele=
ase=C2=A0 has a headline=C2=A0like =E2=80=9CCompany X Announces Record Earn=
ings,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CRecord Revenue Growth,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CReco=
rd Cost Reductions,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CRobust Earnings Despite Global Pan=
demic,=E2=80=9D or whatever the best thing the company can say is. They=E2=
=80=99re never like =E2=80=9CThis Quarter=E2=80=99s Earnings Were Meh and t=
he Stock Is Gonna Go Down,=E2=80=9D or even =E2=80=9CCompany X Announces Ea=
rnings That Are a Lot Higher Than Wall Street Expectations.=E2=80=9D I supp=
ose to the extent you have early=C2=A0merger=C2=A0press release headlines t=
hose are straightforward to trade on.
