=9D on Twitter probably cost him at least hundreds of thousands of dollars =
in legal fees, though he won the defamation=C2=A0lawsuit and didn=E2=80=99t=
 have to pay damages.[2] I dunno. There are about 800 million shares, he ow=
ns about 73 million of them, the stock closed yesterday at $47.01. It would=
 be about $34 billion to buy the rest at that price, but that seems implaus=
ible. At a 20% premium to the current price =E2=80=94=C2=A0about a 43.5% pr=
emium to the price before Musk announced his stake =E2=80=94=C2=A0it would =
be about $41 billion.[3] Figure a zero-ish basis and a top effective federa=
l capital gains tax rate of 23.8% and you need to sell about $55 billion of=
 stock to clear $41 billion of after-tax proceeds. Also one assumes that if=
 Musk announced he was dumping a third of his Tesla stake the stock would g=
o down and he=E2=80=99d have to sell even more to raise all the cash, thoug=
h who knows.[4] Ben Thompson reviews Twitter=E2=80=99s takeover defenses an=
d notes that it has a staggered board, in which one-third of the directors =
are elected each year to three-year terms. This means that the board can=E2=
=80=99t be voted out all at once; it will take at least two years to get ri=
d of a majority of directors. In practice, feh, no, you do not want to be a=
 director on the losing side of this, dragging it out for years.[5] Also, a=
lthough Musk  complains about public markets, he does seem to enjoy his mem=
e-stock ability to influence stock prices. If he took Twitter private there=
=E2=80=99d be no stock price to react to his actions.[6]=C2=A0I.e. if he ow=
ns some shares in street name rather than as a record owner, if he owns som=
e shares through a vehicle other than his trust, etc., he=E2=80=99s more li=
kely to know that than Twitter is.
