der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">a fun story out of Canada</a>:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two Toronto-area programmers for GlobeNewswi=
re, one of the largest wire services in the world, are under investigation =
as part of an insider-trading probe launched by the Ontario Securities Comm=
ission, The Globe and Mail has learned.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=
 regulator alleges that two software developers for Intrado Corporation, th=
e U.S.-based telecommunications company that owns GlobeNewswire, regularly =
texted each other about draft corporate press releases scheduled to be issu=
ed, and executed trades on that material, non-public information. ...</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The court records show that GlobeNewswire mainta=
ins an electronic system for tracking employees who click on news releases =
before they are publicly issued =E2=80=93 which might have offered a potent=
ial clue about employees who traded based on that information.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However, [OSC investigator Anthony] Long said that inv=
estigators had learned of a workaround, where employees could hover their c=
ursor over a partial headline, which would reveal the entire headline =E2=
=80=9Cwithout leaving an audit trail.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/27343269.270594/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMTktMTEtMjYva25vd2luZy10aGUtZnV0dXJlLWlzbi10LXRoYXQtaGVscGZ1bD9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQwNDEyMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA0MTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB689b4dc8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about</a> the fact that the newswire =
hackers, who had the full text of lots of not-yet-public press releases, ha=
d about a 77% success rate: About three-quarters of the time, they would re=
ad a press release and buy (or sell) the stock and the stock would go up (o=
r down), as they predicted. The other quarter of the time they would read t=
he press release and think =E2=80=9Caha good news=E2=80=9D and buy the stoc=
k and then the press release would come out and the stock would go down. It=
 is not easy to read a press release and know if it is good or bad news. Th=
e market might have already expected the good news in the headline, and it =
might instead focus obsessively on the one little bit of bad news in paragr=
aph 11.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It seems like a fun exercise =
to insider trade by=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>mousing over the headlines of u=
nreleased press releases.=C2=A0<em>Every=C2=A0</em>earnings release=C2=A0 h=
as a headline=C2=A0like =E2=80=9CCompany X Announces Record Earnings,=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9CRecord Revenue Growth,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CRecord Cost Red=
uctions,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CRobust Earnings Despite Global Pandemic,=E2=
=80=9D or whatever the best thing the company can say is. They=E2=80=99re n=
ever like =E2=80=9CThis Quarter=E2=80=99s Earnings Were Meh and the Stock I=
s Gonna Go Down,=E2=80=9D or even =E2=80=9CCompany X Announces Earnings Tha=
t Are a Lot Higher Than Wall Street Expectations.=E2=80=9D I suppose to the=
 extent you have early=C2=A0<em>merger=C2=A0</em>press release headlines th=
ose are straightforward to trade on.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"10=
